column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events

During loading there was no signs of product leaking.  Driver moved to the customer scale on site and noticed the turpentine smell and then saw a leak coming from the bottom forward section of the insulation through a weep hole.  Driver moved it to the customer containment area on site.  We formulated a game plan with the shipper to transfer it in to a new trailer.  We also brought in a response team to 'diaper' the trailer in the interim to help contain it.  The transload was successful and the trailer stopped leaking and was cleaned and put on the train back to Chicago.
column169: The trailer just arrived in Chicago this week.  It has not been inspected yet but we are confident this will be a barrel leak.  I do not anticipate that the leak is due to corrosion.  I suspect this is due to a crack in a specific spot where the barrel recieves the most impact pressure when they are lifted on and off the train.  There is a reinforcement kit that will be installed when / if that is the case.  I will update this form once we have confirmation on the root cause - corrective actions.

column168: 08/01/2023, at 10:52 hours, A FRA inspector in the CSXT Manville yard discovered the SHPX222886, a residue tank car of Waste Flammable Liquid, having a vapor release from the top of the car. The rail car was isolated and the shipper, GEOCYCLE, was notified via the waybill’s emergency contact number (877-818-0087).  MEI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car was releasing product vapor due to a faulty vacuum relief valve (VRV). Contractor personnel removed the faulty VRV and installed a pipe plug to stop the release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Marvin Sparks (843-826-1746, marvin.sparks@geocycle.com). The car was held at this location pending further repair and qualification by a certified mobile repair unit or receipt of One Time Move Approval from the FRA.

column168: On August 1st, 2023, FRA Hazmat Inspector observed a possible vapor leak coming from UTLX 679774. The FRA notified the CN Dangerous Goods Officer. The CN Dangerous Goods Officer responded and observed an audible vapor leak from the manway. An attempt was made to check for loose bolts but all manway bolts were secured tightly. All notifications were made. The CN Dangerous goods Officer vented the car and opened the manway and observed damage to gasket. Gasket appeared to be over compressed and had an obvious tear where the observed leak was. The CN Dangerous Goods Officer replaced the manway gasket with a new gasket.  The manway was resecured.  The railcar was released onto destination.

column168: On 08-03-2023 A CN mechanical performing an inbound inspection of train L-57191-03 observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve cap of tank car # UTLX 212943 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Yard Coordinator who in turn made internal emergency notifications per the CN ERP. The tank car was set out to an isolation track (WA90) for inspection by the CN Dangerous Goods Officer. A CN Dangerous Goods Officer responding to the incident. It was immediately noted upon the initial visual inspection that the BOV handle was in the "engaged" position and the BOV handle was not pinned. It was also noted that there was wetness around the threads of the BOV cap with wetness on the ballast directly below. An Ethanol type odor was also present. The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight (could turn by hand) allowing any product collecting within the cap to leak out. Several attempts were made to dis-engage the BOV handle from the valve so it could be pinned in the closed position. These attempts were un-successful. The BOV cap was then removed to determine if the BOV was still leaking as the tank car did not drip any liquids during the DGO's inspection and attempts to dis-engage the BOV handle from the valve. Although there was standing liquid within the BOV cap, the valve itself did not leak after a 20 minute observation. The cap was then re-installed tool tight. A cable seal was utilized to secure the BOV handle in the closed (9 O'clock) position so that it may not open during transit. Home Shop decals were applied to both sides of the tank car, the BOV was red tagged (do not operate). Both the shipper and consignee were notified of the incident and were advised the tank car will require an FRA OTMA 1 prior to being released.

While inspecting tank cars I observed an odor of ammonia and found NATX 35813, residue last contained anhydrous ammonia, to have with the liquid valve open and plug missing.  The plug was in the bottom of the protective housing and ammonia vapor was emitting from the valve.
column169: Closed the liquid valve and secured all the valve & plugs in the protective housing.

column168: ON 08/04/23 at 07:57 AM in the area of MP QC169.9 on the Mohawk Subdivision the M36304 traveling westbound derailed multiple railcars. 9 of the railcars were residue hazardous material railcars. No release of hazardous materials or package failure occurred due to the incident. State Route 5 eastbound was closed due to the derailment and Amtrak passengers were delayed.  HEPACO, a CSX response contractor, and David Scoons, a CSX Senior Manager of Hazardous Materials, responded to the incident to perform assessments of the damaged tank cars as well as ensure that no additional critical damage was sustained during removal of the residue tank cars.  All cars were removed from the derailment site without incident.

column168: SequenceEvent: package was found leaking and wet, it was placed in a bag in a tote and taken to QA for prompt processing. DescribePack: The can had it's like less than a millimeter ajar on the side closest to the seam of the can. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: package was placed in a bag in a tote to contain further leaking.

SequenceEvent: Package was being unloaded from trailer when package handler noticed box was damaged. Manager placed package in bin and brought package to QA for inspection. DescribePack: Box was stained black. Inspection of the inside revealed that an entire side of the box was blackened. The aluminum bucket had a big dent on the side of the bucket that also dented the lid. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a bin and then placed on top of a grate to catch any further release from the package during inspection. Once the leak was found on the top of the aluminum bucket. The item was then placed inside a hazmat bin to prevent anymore movement.

SequenceEvent: The package was left in QA wrapped in a flimsy plastic bag, leaking product with a strong fume.  We immediately placed it in a hazmat bag and a black tote and removed it from the work area. DescribePack: One of the caps of the two containers and worked itself off the spout. Through movement of transport much of the contents escaped from the bottle. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: We immediately placed it in a hazmat bag and a black tote and removed it from the work area.  A DPR and ISF was completed and all contents, plus box and other items affected were placed in a Hazmat salvage drum.

SequenceEvent: The outer pkg contained 4 plastic jugs of chemical drain cleaner.  The jugs had screw-on caps.  At some point during the pkg's shipment the vibration of transit caused the jugs' screw-on caps to loosen.  3 of the jugs' caps were only slightly loose while the 4th jug's cap was found completely off the jug. Chemical odor and pkg dampness prompted inspection at the delivery station.  The pkg was placed in a plastic tub when first discovered and was sent to the station's QA area for eventual inspection and processing. DescribePack: Again, vessels that employ screw-on caps are prone to having the caps loosen from the vibration of transit alone.  3 of the 4 jugs' caps were found to be slightly loose - the 4th jug's cap was completely off. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The caps on the jugs were tightened, the jugs were wiped down with paper towels, and contaminated cardboard was contained in a plastic tub.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: XPO Logistics terminal XWO experienced a release from a 2950-pound battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of battery acid released impacting multiple areas of concrete to include a 10' x 10' and 20' x 10' areas, a 40' x 1' area of the ramp and a 5' x 5' area where the battery was sitting. The battery tipped over in transit causing 6 of the caps to be lost, resulting in a release. Terminal personnel removed the battery from the trailer to a dock area, which resulted in acid being released to multiple areas. The crew worked the absorbents deployed by XPO into the impacted areas and collected them into drums. The areas were then neutralized with sodium bicarb. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged battery was up righted and secured to a new pallet, with poly sheeting taped over it to prevent further release. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal NCH experienced a UN3267 Sikadur 52 Part B release from (3) 1-gallon metal pails. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-gallons of product released to an 8' x 2' area of the trailer floor and an 8' x 8' area of the concrete lot below the trailer. The crew advised the lids of the pails were crushed due to improper loading causing the release. Oil Gator was deployed and worked into the impacted areas. Once complete, the areas were pH strip tested to confirm neutralization. All waste was then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

I AM NOW AWAITING FOR THE DISPOSITION FROM PGH.

column168: On August 14, CN Transportation crews observed liquid dripping down the sides on UTLX 125075. The railcar was isolated and all required notifications were made. CN response contractor responded to the site. Upon approaching the railcar, liquid was observed streaming down the sides of the railcar and pooling on the ground below the railcar. Under closer inspection, liquid was observed coming from the liquid eduction line. Attempts were made to tighten the cap and were unsuccessful. The pressure was relieved which stopped the leak. The liquid eduction cap was again attempted to be tightened again; 7 additional turns were achieved. The cap was removed to check if a gasket was installed. No gasket was observed. A gasket was installed in the liquid eduction cap and teflon tape was applied to the threads. The liquid eduction cap was properly installed. The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated. The railcar was released onto destination.

First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 3ft-by-2ft area of the concrete dock floor and an 8ft-by-6ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that three (3) gallons of material was released. First Call Environmental personnel removed 29 boxes that contained two (2) 1-gallon plastic jugs that were impacted by the released material. The non-damaged boxes (a total 67 boxes) were restacked and shipped onto the consignee. First Call Environmental personnel deployed a neutralizer to the impacted areas and First Call Environmental personnel recovered the spent material and containerized it into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted cardboard and plastic jugs were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite in a secure location at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization.  The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: On August 18, 2023, at 0239 ET, XPO Logistics terminal LTU suffered a cargo related release of UN3149 “AcidiShine” to the trailer floor and asphalt lot below from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. On August 18, 2023, at 0530 ET, contractors arrived onsite. Crew confirmed one 55-gallon poly drum of UN3149 “AcidiShine” released due to a pallet nail puncture. Approximately 30-gallons released to a 5’ x 30’ area of the trailer floor and a 10’ x 5’ area of the asphalt lot below. The impacted surfaces and debris were neutralized with a vinegar solution and confirmed neutral with pH test strips. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The empty damaged drum was containerized into an 85-gallon vented poly drum. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were collected into a 55-gallon vented poly drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A WET PKG. RESPONDER DONNED ALL PPE AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP AND PROCESS THROUGH PROPER DMP PROCEDURES.

While loading an outbound trailer of totes at Veolia's 10-day facility in Port Allen, LA a forklift punctured the IBC. The forks of the lift were extending approximately 3-4 inches beyond the underneath of the IBC and while repositioning the tote the fork made contact with another tote behind it, resulting in a ~3" gash at the bottom corner of the container. The tote began leaking rapidly and spilled ~150 gallons within a 10 minute span. The material flooded the back of the box van and the surrounding concrete of the dock area. The Veolia team quickly began blocking off the storm drain located in the dock area with spill pads and oil dry, as well as blocking off the back of the trailer to slow the pace of the material leaking out the trailer. The spill was promptly cleaned up and absorbent material was containerized. The remaining material in the damaged tote was transferred into a new container.
column169: Additional training on tote-specific handling with a forklift will help prevent any further incidents. Another process related suggestion would be to identify opportunities where our team could minimize the need to move the containers as much as possible, for example setting the material up to be delivered directly to the disposal facility when feasible instead of offloading and loading again at the 10-Day facility.

column168: A Memphis spill agent was called to an outbound sort operations for a class 9 in a fiberboard box with signs of a release. The spill agent was told that the fiberboard box had been dropped while it was being unloaded from a cart. While investigating the fiberboard box there was a single steel drum inside. The top chime of the steel drum had been damaged and was the source of the release. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and a new declaration will be needed for movement.
As the MP was being pulled out of the trailer, the box of adhesives fell over and spilled onto the dock floor. Only one pail of adhesives ~spilled.
column169: Exercise caution when removing hazardous freight from a trailer.

SequenceEvent: Tape failed on the bottom closures prompting the pkg to be sent to the Hazmat Processing Area for inspection and reporting. Upon inspection of the carton interior it was discovered a small amount of liquid had leaked wetting only the inside of the carton and dried droplets were found on the inner containers. The pkg and contents were placed in a lined Hazmat bin when the failure of the closures was found and the pkg remains in the bin at this time. DescribePack: Loose caps on 2 x 2.5 gal plastic bottles. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Pkg placed in lined Hazmat bin.

column168: SequenceEvent: Carton removed from unload wet placed in damage area for inspection DescribePack: Loose cap DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Cap tighen bottles wiped for loose liquid place in a hazardous material bag, then place inside a white salvage drum along with all material used.

SequenceEvent: Leaking metal drum discovered in middle area. Immediately placed in a lined tote and taken to HMPA staging pallet for further investigation. DescribePack: 1 inch crack with two smaller branches found on metal ridge of bottom of drum. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PPE donned, SDS found attached to drum, ventilation used.

SequenceEvent: The package was being unloaded this morning and the package handler noticed the box wet, they immediately notified a manger who placed the damage hazmat in a red bin. The hazmat was then taken to the hazmat cage with the vent on. DescribePack: The hazmat was packed inside a box too big for the hazmat with only bubble wrap. The bubble wrap was not securely over the hazmat allowing the hazmat to slip out of the bubble wrap and the hazmat was being shipped loose inside the box inadequate for its size. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The hazmat was placed in a red hazmat bin brought to the hazmat cage with the ventilation system on.

SequenceEvent: hazmat was discovered this morning on the inbound as needing a relabel because the original label was destroyed. someone set it aside and placed a 33 (address search) on the package. this evening the HAP specialist noticed that the package was not in UNPOP packaging and had been repacked by someone at Fedex Ground. He brought it over to the damage area for HESS specialist to inspect later. Around 7:15pm, HESS specialist had the time to inspect and found that the bottles inside had been placed inside a blue hazmat bag and ziptied shut. HESS specialist noticed liquid inside with the bottles and placed it in a lined tote, moving it to the drain mats in the incoming damaged hazmat/LQ area. in-house cleanup, awaiting disposition. DescribePack: three bottles leaked due to loose caps. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: placed in lined tote, moved to drain mats

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: SequenceEvent: Found the box in the hazmat cage, upon inspection found the box damaged. once opened found that one of four glass bottles of methanol has broken and spilled out its contents. the box the box does look as if it were dropped or crushed hard on one side. this is on the same side as the damaged bottle. DescribePack: there is a dent in the box just over halfway up it. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: all was put into a plastic spill bag and then into a hazmat tote, lastly into the hazmat cage.

SequenceEvent: The cap on one of the bottles came loose and an internal leakage resulted. Upon being discovered, the box was brought to QA to be worked on. SequenceEvent: Driver found box leaking on delivery truck and placed inside several plastic bags to bring back to the station for inspection. SDS says Class 3 PG II but box only had printed directional arrows and no Hazmat service. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Driver placed box inside several plastic bags and gave to QA for inspection when he returned to the station

column168: On Aug 21st during the sort a package was found leaking on the belt.   The package was not marked or labeled as dangerous goods on the outside of the package.   Further investigation after opening the package found that there were twelve cans of a two part resin, six cans of part A and six cans of part B. The leaking receptacle PTM&W PT2475A was non-DG according to the safety data sheet, approximately 50ml of the product spilled out.   The other six cans contained PTM&W PT2475B, which according to the safety data sheet are UN1760, Corrosive liquid n.o.s., 8, III.  The package was contained in a salvage drum, and is being held at the station pending further disposition due to the undeclared element.

column168: SequenceEvent: I found the original outer packaging in recycle bin, soaked and still had the Hazardous materials shipping papers still on one side. Shipping label and Dimond labels were removed from original outer packaging. As we do not dispose of contaminated packaging in this manner, I checked the paperwork for TRK # and looked up the Ftrack. There was a 10 Scan on 08/25/23 and nothing else till 08/26/23 at around 1am. there was no DPR done or a 40 scan for repack and inspection. I have no information about how the original package was found or the condition it was in or if there was any inner packaging, I could tell by the original packaging that the inner containers had been leaking. I was able to locate the repacked contents inspect them. Upon inspection I found 2 contains were still wet and one container was missing a noticeable amount of liquid compared to the other. There was also noted wetness on the other inner package box. And it had been tapped over. Wet outer packaging was placed in a beg. I tightened the caps on the containers and placed all outer and inner packaging in a bag inside a yellow hazmat bin. I performed a DPR and ISF once I found the repacked Hazmat containers. DescribePack: As I have no information on the original packaging, the only thing I can say for sure is that the caps were loose on the inside containers. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Unknown

A Memphis spill agent was dispatched to the dangerous goods building for a leaking fiberboard box. While investigating the fiberboard box the spill agent observed four plastic bottles inside. One of the four plastic bottles had a loose cap. That bottle released all of its contents inside of the fiberboard box. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper will be contacted for an amended declaration for movement.

A fiberboard box was discovered with signs of a release during sort operations at the CLER location. The fiberboard box contained four plastic buckets of a substance identified as a UN3082. The lid on one of the four buckets came loose and released its contents inside of the box. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package. The fiberboard box didn't have any hazardous material markings or paperwork attached.  This was a multi piece shipment and all three packages are being held for FAA inspection.

A Spill agent at the Indianapolis hub was contacted about a leaking package found in a drive lane.  The fiberboard box had been crushed and the three plastic bottles inside were all damaged. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and will be disposed of as hazardous materials.

column168: SequenceEvent: We received a trailer from the Syracuse facility. When opened the HAZMAT was discovered on the bottom of an entire wall of the trailer under immense pressure from all the other packages on top. The package handler that was assigned to the trailer at the time had seen this event and called out that there was a leaking HAZMAT present inside the trailer. A manager then advised them to step out of the trailer and continue working elsewhere. After it was discovered the QA employee at the time went over with a HAZMAT bucket and picked it up and swiftly put the HAZMAT in a salvage drum. The proper steps were NOT followed completely. The SDS was never pulled when it was found leaking. DescribePack: When inspected later on the next day, it was discovered that a leaking cap was causing the slow leak. The weight from other packages on top of the HAZMAT caused a cap to come loose. DurationRel: 5 and MitigateEffect: Package was immediately placed in a salvage drum

SequenceEvent: Package was found on van with wet on bottom and side, wrapped up in 2 plastic bags. Package was removed from van and placed inside of a hazmat plastic bag and then placed inside of a red hazmat tote.  . DescribePack: 1 of the 4 bottles had a loose cap with a broken seal. The cap was re-tightened. There was no noticeable damage to the package besides it being wet. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed inside a hazmat bag, then folded closed and placed in a hazmat tote.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LDA experienced a battery acid release from a 1044-pound UN2794 Battery, filled with acid. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 8-gallons of product released impacting an 8’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and a 5’ x 3’ area of the concrete lot below due to improper loading. The impacted areas were neutralized with sodium bicarbonate and then collected with absorbents. The impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged battery was shrink wrapped with absorbent pads and secured to a pallet. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

HES personnel deployed absorbents to the released material and swept them in using hand tools. All UN1915-impacted absorbents were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The crew then overpacked the damaged 55-gallon drum in one (1) 95-gallon overpack for disposal.

column168: On 8/13/2023, a World Fuel Services, Inc. (WFS) tanker truck and driver were dispatched to the American Heritage vessel located at the Public Landing in downtown Cincinnati, OH for a delivery. The WFS driver arrived on site around 0830 and completed site inspection with vessel personnel, then begin the delivery. At approximately, 0900 the WFS driver saw product leaking from the truck’s pumping equipment and immediately hit the emergency shut off stopping product flow. Five gallons of No. 2 diesel fuel spilled from piping where a gasket had ruptured between the truck’s meter and pump. The spill impacted the concrete parking lot and up to a gallon of diesel impacted the Ohio River at mile marker 469.9. Both WFS and the vessel personnel took action to contained and the cleaned up the spill. The vessel deployed a boom and WFS used spill pads to contained the spill. The WFS driver notified the Cincinnati Operations Manager who then notified the HSSE Manager at 0930. Additional WFS personnel and the Operations Manager were deployed to site with spill cleaned up supplies at this time. And, HEPACO, WFS OSRO, was notified and dispatched to the site. WFS notified the NRC at 0955 of the incident. The Ohio EPA and the Hamilton EMA were notified of the spill between 1008 and 1015. By 1100 the spill had been cleaned up. The spill was cleaned up using absorbent booms, oil dry, and spills pads. Both WFS and vessel personnel cleaned up the spill and HEPACO was called off. The tanker unit was placed out of service until repairs could be completed. WFS later completed the delivery with different equipment, demobilize, and left the site.
column169: World Fuel Service, Inc. (WFS) reviews and investigates all incidents to determine root cause and what corrective actions need to be implemented to prevent any reoccurrences. The spill occurred because of an equipment failure. A gasket in the piping between the truck’s meter and pump ruptured. This resulted in a five gallon spill. The unit was taken out of service until it was repaired. And, new WFS tanker trucks will be outfitted with United States Coast Guard certified hoses so that newer tanker trucks can be used for future deliveries to these type of locations. These units will be added to the facility response plan. And, these units will be outfitted with additional spill supplies and a new procedure will be implemented to place a precautionary absorbent boom down between the tanker truck and vessel for future over the water deliveries. During the September Operations Safety Meetings, all drivers will be brief on the incident and reminded on the importance of never leaving the point of discharge while product is flowing.

column168: An employee was offloading a trailer at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Richmond, CA and was staging the drums outside of the trailer prior to receiving the drums to the designated location. He was utilizing a forklift in which he was approaching 4 drums that were palletized. The employee did not realize that the pallet was not a standard size pallet and was not as deep. The forks exceeded the length of the pallet and hit the drum that was on the opposing side. The forks hit the drum roughly an inch above the bottom chime resulting in the drum getting damaged and a small pinhole leak occurred. The overall duration of the incident was a less than 10 minutes and it was determined that approximately 4 to 5 cups of material leaked out. The Veolia employees on site were able to contain the spill and place the damaged drum into a salvage drum.
column169: The Veolia employee was immediately removed from all forklift operations and was retrained and re-evaluated.  The employee was trained to observe for difference in pallet sizes along with making sure he gets off the forklift to make accurate determination of the length of the forks in comparison to the pallet. In addition, he was trained to ensure that there is proper separation between drums and pallets when completing the initial staging of the drum when offloading.

column168: On 8/02/2023 an employee at Veolia's Schenectady, NY 10 day intransit facility was loading drums from a trailer into another trailer when the employee scratched the side of a 55-gallon steel drum with the drum cart while placing it in an outbound trailer. The leak occurred when the employee was moving the drums into the trailer and the employee misjudged the clearance to another drum. The 55 gallon drum containing flammable corrosive liquids was scraped with a drum cart which resulted in causing a leak from the drum. Approximately one pint of liquid leaked out of the impacted drum. Liquid was only observed on trailer right below drum and did not leak out of the vehicle.   The drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum, the spill cleaned up, and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent material. The duration of release is anticipated to be less than 1 minute as the employee immediately noticed the accident and began taking measures to contain the spill.
column169: On 8/02/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation revealed that the employee misjudged the distance from the drum cart to the nearby drum that was hit. The hole was on the bottom of the drum and was from scraping the side of the drum. The employee was instructed to be more careful maneuvering the drum cart.

column168: Driver was distracted trying to pick up spilled soda off of the floor and took his eyes off of the road when his Semi left the right side of the road. When he looked back up he realized that all wheels were off of the road and tried to correct. When his pup was coming back on the highway it rolled over on the drivers side of the pup. Driver continued to try to get control of the rig and dragged the pup for approximately 1/4 mile, spilling fuel the whole way, until the equipment came to a stop on the westbound lane. Upon inspection of the crash site the driver observed several spot fires so he grabbed his 20# extinguisher and attempted to put them out, Shortly after stopping he observed that the tank was on fire so he unhooked his main from the pup and moved the truck down the road. The pup became engulfed in flames and was a total loss as well as the 3500 gal of Diesel fuel. Since that time Hunt and Sons has put on safety meetings at all locations for "Distracted Driving" and are in the process of turning on the in-cab cameras to help coach individuals who become distracted while driving.
column169: We will deliver safety meetings and turn on in-cab cameras to help prevent future incidents like this.

column168: On August 23, 2023, CN Transportation crews reported a strong odor near RCRX 2119 while switching in CN Baton Rouge Yard.  The railcar was isolated.  All required notifications were made.  CN Response contractor responded and upon arrival smelled an odor around the railcar.  Upon closer investigation, the cause of the release was determined to be 3 of the 4 liquid line blind flange bolts were missing and all 4 of the vapor valve blind flange bolts were found to be less than tool tight.  The missing bolts were found on the pressure plate of the tank car. The missing bolts were reinstalled, and the loose bolts were tightened which stopped the release.  The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated, and the railcar was released and allowed to continue onto destination.

On August 31, 2023, FRA hazmat Inspector observed liquid dripping down the sides of railcar UTLX 95658 (L / UN 3082, Environmentally hazardous Substance, Liquid, N.O.S) while inspecting a track at CN Mays Yard.  CN Contractor responded and observed liquid leaking down the sides of the railcar and dripping onto the ground in several locations.  Upon closer inspection, the manway bolts were found to be tool tight but still allowed product to leak.  The manway was opened so the gasket could be checked.  The gasket was determined to be heavily worn and deteriorated.  The gasket was replaced.  The manway was resecured.  The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated.  The railcar was released onto destination.

column168: On August 30, 2023, two (2) one-gallon pails of concrete stain acid (UN1263) were punctured with a forklift and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the loading dock floor and adjacent boxes. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. The crew identified the impacted pallet, removed the damaged containers, removed the impacted boxes, and restacked the unaffected cargo. The damaged pails were collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. HES personnel utilized absorbents, absorbent pads, and neutralizer to remediate the impacted areas. The impacted solids were collected with hand tools. All impacted boxes, absorbents, and absorbent pads were collected and containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums. All three (3) drums were labeled and staged onsite for disposal by R+L.

column168: On August 30, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of paint was punctured by a forklift and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the concrete surface. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted surface. LSH personnel overpacked the damaged 55-gallon drum in one (1) 85-gallon drum. The crew then deployed granular absorbents to the concrete and swept them in using hand tools. All spent absorbents and clean up debris were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. The crew returned the next day to commence power washing procedures. A boom was deployed to contain the area while crews pressure washed. One hundred and fifty (150) gallons of paint-rinseate were collected into three (3) 55-gallon drums. One (1) drum of spent absorbents, boom, and cleanup debris was also generated as waste. All four (4) 55-gallon drums of waste were staged on-site for further handling by R+L personnel.

column168: On 08-31-23 at 1321 a FRA Inspector in the CSXT Edgewood Yard discovered UTLX645049, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Terpentine leaking vapors from manway. The car was isolated and Georgia-Pacific LLC was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2023083100164). Hepaco LLC, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapors were being released from the manway. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper contact Tom Davidson and 404-376-9550. Contractor personnel opened manway and found that gasket was damaged, Hepaco installed a new manway gasket and tool tightened manway safety bolts. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.

column168: Around 6:30am, the yard personnel were in the process of transferring containers to different trailers when they noticed a tote that might have a possible leak around the valve. They prepped an empty tote in the event there was a need to transfer the material out of the tote. Once they were all prepped, they checked the valve handle to make sure it was fully in the closed position. When the outlet cap was unscrewed, the material shot out of the valve due to a missing ball valve. Over half of the material was captured in the second tote and approximately 125 gals of the material released to the asphalt around the load dock. There was no release to the environment. The yard team quickly controlled the release with berms, absorbents, and vermiculite/floor dry and proceeded to clean up the material.
column169: Ingenium provided the client with the reconditioned tote. Employees will be expected to inspect totes before taking to the clients. In addition, Ingenium will be transitioning to new totes or totes in which only the cages are reconditioned.

column168: 1. A customer stopped FA during boarding and said her vape was hot and asked him to throw it away 2. Customer mentioned the device may have been damaged while in her bag 3. FA noticed light smoke(possibly vape?) coming from the device 4. FA asked customer to wait as throwing it away may not be safe 5. Customer had a paper towel(possibly napkin) and wrapped the vape inside 6. Customer essentially put it in the FAs hands to dispose of it 7. FA immediately took it to the forward galley and submerged it in a cup of water to contain/cool 8. FA noted the device did not feel hot when carrying it to the front 9. CSR appeared moments later and FA notified CSR 10. FA asked CSR what to do with the device 11. CSR then took the cup of water, with the vape submerged inside, off the aircraft 12. Later, the same CSR advised FA that she had given it over to her supervisor 13. FA is unsure of CSR name or CSR supervisor name 14. FA is unsure of customer ID or seat number as it occurred during boarding with many customers standing in the aisle 15. FA confirmed the device was a vape, but did not unwrap from towel or pull out of water to inspect

column168: While loading freight into trailer forklift operator struck a pail that was already staged in the trailer with the forkblade on his forklift consequently puncturing the pail and contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the damaged pail.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: While freight was being loaded into trailer forklift operator went to pickup a pallet and when he did the forkblades hit two pails that had fallen through the pallet because one of the pallet boards was broken. As a result, when the forkblade hit the two pails it slightly punctured them and consequently contributed to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the two punctured pails.
column169: It's hard for a forklift operator to see freight that has fallen through the pallet when one of the pallet boards is broken. Perhaps if a piece of dunnage like a sheet of cardboard was placed on the pallet first or more sturdier pallets were used they could have prevented this unintentional release.

column168: On August 9, 2023, TransWood Carriers contacted ERTS to request assistance with the clean-up of a 400-gallon release of Biodiesel at a Flying J truck stop.  It was reported that a storm drain, and public street were impacted by the release. Before the contractor was dispatched the Fire Department was on site and he advised the storm drain was impacted but it did not reach the outfall. The Fire Department placed tons of sand on the impacted areas.  HMRI arrived on site advised that three drains were impacted but the last drain the product settled in the basin. A vac truck was used to recover all free-standing product and absorbents and boom were placed to collect any remaining product.  An estimated 640 gallons of oily water was recovered and transferred to 330-gallon totes.   HMRI completed the cleanup generating one roll of containing impacted absorbents and two 330-gallon poly totes of impacted water.  The roll off remained on site and the totes were staged at the contractor's shop until profiled and proper disposal.

column168: PVS Minibulk Driver was unloading hydrochloric acid into a tank when the driver noticed the product was leaking out of a 55-gallon drum that was being used as an overflow tank. A valve on the customers tank was left open and the product was flowing into the overflow drum which had a crack in the bottom of it. The driver then shut off his valves from the truck to stop the unloading process to allow customer to close the valve. The product was flowing out of the cracked drum onto a concrete pad for 5 minutes. The customer took responsibility for the release and replaced the cracked drum to ensure there would not be a release in the future if the overflow tank would be utilized. The product was used in the cleaning process of the concrete pad where it was spilled.
column169: The customer aknowleded a procedural error in not closing all the valves before the unloading process begun. PVS Minibulk discussed this incident at our monthly safety meeting on the importance of checking all valves and monitoring the entire line during the unloading process. We discussed with the customer the importance of double checking all valves before the unloading process begins and checking the integrity of the overflow drum periodically to ensure there are no leaks.

column168: Around 6:30am, the yard personnel were in the process of transferring containers to different trailers when they noticed a tote that might have a possible leak around the valve. They prepped an empty tote in the event there was a need to transfer the material out of the tote. Once they were all prepped, they checked the valve handle to make sure it was fully in the closed position. When the outlet cap was unscrewed, the material shot out of the valve due to a missing ball valve. Over half of the material was captured in the second tote and approximately 125 gals of the material released to the asphalt around the load dock. There was no release to the environment. The yard team quickly controlled the release with berms, absorbents, and vermiculite/floor dry and proceeded to clean up the material.
column169: Ingenium provided the client with the reconditioned tote. Employees will be expected to inspect totes before taking to the clients. In addition, Ingenium will be transitioning to new totes or totes in which only the cages are reconditioned.

Approximately 8:00 am on August 10, 2023, our driver stated that he noticed a transmission light on his dash, and he felt the trailer dragging. he then heard a loud pup while driving EB on US highway 6, thinking he blew a tire. He did not see any debris as he looked to his rear view mirror, and he stated the traffic was very heavy with no shoulder to safely pull off the road on a 2 lane road. So he proceeded to the nearest safe haven so he could inspect the problem. He approached the Fuel Mart on Hwy 6 and US 23, and pulled off of the road. As he walked to the rear of the trailer to inspect the incident, he found it to be on fire around the back axle and tires. He proceeded to get the fire extinguisher from his truck, but was unable to extinguish the fire. Another bystander had already called 911, so he disconnected his truck from the trailer.  To the best of our knowledge, we believe that while he was driving, he either blew a brake chamber, or had an air leak causing the axle to drag. Which subsequently caused the tires to drag, and initiate the transmission light on his dash. Followed by the tire to blow out and getting hot enough to spark a fire burning the tires. By the time the Fire Department arrived the fire was hot enough to burn a hole through the back side wall of the aluminum trailer.
column169: After meeting with our driver and taking his statement on the incident, Our conclusion of the incident is, the driver needed to stop as soon as possible after he noticed the transmission light, and hearing what he thought was a tire blowing out. Our recommendation to him was to stop as soon as possible. With the heavy traffic and a small shoulder that he did not feel safe to pull over on, he should possibly call 911 for assistance to help him get off of the 2 lane highway and help control traffic which was very heavy at that particular time.

column162: DIRECTOR OF COMPLIANCE AND REGULATORY AFFAIRS
column168: On 8/14/2023 no defects were noted during pre-trip. Jerry left the Centreville yard for St. Rose, LA at approx. 8:15am CST.   Stopped for diesel fuel in MS and no defects were noted prior to leaving the gas station. Jerry noted that traffic was moderate with some construction zones that caused him to use his brakes more often.   At approx. 1:00pm CST Jerry was passing a car in the left lane at 70 mph. and noticed smoke coming from under the rear portion of the trailer. Heard a loud bang and pulled to the right side of the road as soon as he was able.   Jerry grabbed the fire extinguisher and noticed flames coming from the passenger side of the tractor below the 5th wheel - he emptied the extinguisher out and ran when unable to control. He called 911 at this time.   The flames from the tractor engulfed the trailer and caused pressure relief valves to discharge propane and the propane ignited spreading to all 1344 cylinders being affected.   Traffic was stopped in the Northbound lanes and first responders arrived within 10 min. and immediately secured the scene. The fire and release lasted about 30 min. to an hour while local first responders ensured the flames didn't spread. The interstate was shutdown for close to three hours and the scene was cleaned up.
column169: Due to the nature of mechanical failure there are no recommendations at this time.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: At 1:00 on 8/24/2023 Kansas City Southern Railway's(DBA CPKCR) Rosebluff yard in Westlake, LA reported tank car UTLX 130533 containing UN 1789, HYDROCHLORIC ACID Ieaking from the top of the car. The Environmental& Hazmat Department mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to mitigate the release. Upon arrival, responders found one of the four bolts securing the liquid line four bolt blind flange primary closure not tool tight Responders vented the rail car to stop the release and tightened the four bolt flange bolt tool tight, approximately 3 full turns. Responders also found one of the nuts used to secure the all-thread bolt on the bottom spool of the liquid line was not tool tight against the spool flange. This nut could not be secured tool tight The nut was removed and replaced with another nut that was rendered tool tight to the spool flange for proper securement The removed nut was found to be rusted and had stripped threads. Atmospheric temperature was thought to have caused sufficient thermal expansion to push liquid up the liquid line and by the loose four bolt blind flange closure and/or the spool. The defective all-thread bolt on the spool was located directly below the nut that was tool tightened on the blind flange. UTLX 130533 was monitored for an additional 20 minutes to ensure that the leak had been secured, with no leaks detected. Rendering both nuts tool tight stopped the leak. The estimated release Is 1 gallon. The released commodity on the car was neutralized. Once the release was mitlgated, the car was returned to transportation. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered In this package Is not known to the carrier. This carrier

column168: Driver arrived at customer location to fill a Dimethylformamide(DMF) tank. He verified the tank, quantity, and connection prior to starting to pump. Driver inspected the connections and proceeded to check on the internal valve, which he closed and opened again. After doing so a cap on the rear of the trailer popped off and product started coming out of the open pipe. Driver shutdown the pump and approximately 90 gallons of DMF spilled into the customer's containment. The cause of the release was the result of a faulty outlet cap. During the investigation it was determined that there was no isolation valve installed behind the cap.

column168: On 08/31/2023, at 0619, personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered UTLX 755938, a residue tank car of Petroleum Gases, Liquified, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Maryland Department of the Environment, and National Response Center were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2023-0831-00068). The local fire department responded to the site and observed the A-End liquid valve partially open and secondary closure plug less than tool tight, and actively releasing lading. Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and confirmed a partially open liquid valve and less than tool tight secondary closure plug. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Jeff Dean of Tri Gas and Oil, phone 410-310-6354. Contractor personnel closed the valve and properly installed the secondary closure plug, thus securing the release. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 119 NARRI: 90

column168: Driver arrived at the customer in Bumside, LA. When he stopped at the guard shack to check in, he noticed product coming from his crash box on top of the trailer. Driver climbed on top of the trailer to see where the product was coming from. Upon inspection, driver could see that the grommet where the air/nitrogen line hooks up had a crack in it. At this time it appeared this was what had caused the leak. Mechanic was called out to make repairs by replacing the grommet. Once mechanic got on scene, he discovered that the valve had been left open causing the product to come out of the line. Mechanic replaced the cracked grommet and closed the valve. Environmental company was called out to clean the product off the ground and to clean the trailer. Driver was able to off load without any further issues.

column168: SequenceEvent: Manager called out leaking gas in his work area. Package was located at outbounds. Upon arrival, I smelled gas. Upon observation, I observed there was leaking gas from the inside of the package. A small amount of gas leakage on the floor was covered with absorbent powder. Package was immediately taken to the HazMat cage. DescribePack: The inside of the package had gasoline inside the tank of the lawn mower. It spilled out of the gas tank onto the box and to the outside of the package. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Absorbent powder was immediately poured on the work area floor.
